<section xml:id="sec-l-hopitals-rule">
  <title>L'Hôpital's rule</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use L'Hôpital's Rule to evaluate limits where numerator and denominator both approach zero or infinity.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret limits in terms of relative growth rates.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use algebraic or logarithmic rewrites to handle other indeterminate forms.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>\limit{x\to a}f(x)=\limit{x\to a}g(x)=0</m>, then
        <me>
          \limit{x\to a}\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}=\limit{x\to a}\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Same goes for if <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are both approaching infinity
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        For other indeterminate forms, use algebraic massage or logarithms
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
